{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486930"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:50:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:50:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"210"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/210"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.57,0.01,0.05,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"210"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46934"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/210"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"210"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31708"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"251"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"1393"},{"type":"tags","id":"1536"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"514"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11566"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44452"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46934"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a two-month history of anorexia and unintentional weight loss of 10 kg. He has not had any changes in bowel motions, nausea, vomiting, or night sweats, but has noticed increased fatigue lately. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, his vital signs are within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals a mass in the epigastric region. He is referred for endoscopy, which reveals an adenocarcinoma of the proximal stomach.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most appropriate to determine if the patient is a suitable candidate for curative treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Staging laparoscopy","CT chest, abdomen and pelvis","Serum tumour markers","Endoscopic ultrasound","PET scan"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EProviding the patient is otherwise in good health, the most important determinant as to the suitability of curative treatment for this gastric cancer will be the presence or absence of metastatic spread. Of the investigations provided, \u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest, abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most practical to provide a reasonable assessment of loco-regional disease and the presence of any metastases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the CT shows no signs of distant metastases, a \u003Cstrong\u003Estaging laparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended before resection to exclude peritoneal spread. If peritoneal disease is detected, then any planned treatment will be effectively palliative. A staging laparoscopy could avoid an unnecessary non-therapeutic laparotomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopic ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E may be beneficial in evaluating an early tumour; however, given the presence of a mass on clinical examination and history of weight loss, a CT is necessary to look for advanced loco-regional disease and distant metastatic spread.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EPET scan\u003C/strong\u003E, although useful in recognition of peritoneal spread and lymph node metastases, is inferior to CT in recognising loco-regional disease. The uptake of PET by gastric cancers is variable, making it a relatively unreliable staging tool for these cancers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum tumour markers\u003C/strong\u003E, although if raised may indicate advanced disease, are not useful in definitively staging gastric cancer, and cannot reliably differentiate between localised and metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The CT scan is an important tool in the staging of gastrointestinal tract cancers."],"references":["Correa P. Gastric cancer: overview. Gastroenterol Clin North Am. 2013;42(2):211-7. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23639637/","Malaj A, Bilaj F, Shahini A, Miraka M. CT/MRI accuracy in detecting and determining preoperative stage of gastric adenocarcinoma in Albania. Contemp Oncol (Pozn). 2017;21(2):168-173. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28947888/","Mukkamalla SKR, Recio-Boiles A, Babiker HM. Gastric Cancer. [Updated 2023 Jul 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459142/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31708"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"210"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31708"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-13T22:05:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-13T22:05:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"210"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46934"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09